messages.content:
Analyze this scene and tell me what could go wrong:

orb Player { position: [0,0,0] }
orb Enemy { position: [10,0,0], health: 100 }
orb HealthPack { position: [5,0,5], traits: ["collectible"] }

Looking at this graph, I see **three isolated nodes**:

```
[Player]     [Enemy]     [HealthPack]
    ○           ○            ○
 (no connections between any of them)
```

**Problems:**

1. **Player is just a position marker** - no way to move, interact, or take damage
2. **Enemy has health but no behavior** - can't attack, patrol, or die
3. **HealthPack has collectible trait but no handler** - nothing happens when collected
4. **No logic block** - zero event flows defined

**What could go wrong at runtime:**
- Player can't do anything
- Enemy just stands there
- Collecting HealthPack does nothing (trait promises interaction but delivers nothing)
- Game is static - nothing can happen

**To make this functional, you need flows:**

```holo
logic {
  // Enemy → Player damage flow
  every(2000) {
    if (distance(Enemy, Player) < 3) {
      Player.health -= 10
    }
  }

  // HealthPack → Player heal flow
  on_collect("HealthPack") {
    Player.health += 25
    despawn(HealthPack)
  }

  // Player death flow
  on_health_zero("Player") {
    game_over()
  }
}
```

Now the graph has life:
```
[Enemy] ──damages──→ [Player] ←──heals── [HealthPack]
```

A quest system is a **directed acyclic graph (DAG)** - tasks flow forward, can branch, but don't loop back.

**Quest as a flow graph:**
```
[Start] ──accept──→ [Objective 1] ──complete──→ [Objective 2]
                          │                          │
                          │                          ↓
                          │               ┌─── [Objective 3a]
                          │               │          │
                          └── optional ──→│          ↓
                                          │    [Turn In]
                                          │          │
                                          └─── [Objective 3b]
                                                     │
                                                     ↓
                                                [Reward]
```

**In .holo, quests are state machines:**

```holo
composition "Quest System" {

  template "Quest" {
    state {
      status: "available"  // available → active → complete
      current_objective: 0
      progress: {}
    }

    action accept() {
      this.status = "active"
      emit("quest_accepted", this)
    }

    action advance() {
      this.current_objective += 1
      if (this.current_objective >= this.objectives.length) {
        this.complete()
      }
    }

    action complete() {
      this.status = "complete"
      emit("quest_complete", this)
    }
  }

  template "Objective" {
    state {
      type: "kill"  // kill, collect, talk, reach
      target: ""
      required: 1
      current: 0
    }

    action increment() {
      this.current += 1
      if (this.current >= this.required) {
        emit("objective_complete", this)
      }
    }
  }

  // Quest data (the graph structure)
  spatial_group "Quests" {
    object "Quest_SlayGoblins" using "Quest" {
      title: "Goblin Trouble"
      giver: "NPC_Guard"
      objectives: [
        { type: "talk", target: "NPC_Guard" },
        { type: "kill", target: "Goblin", required: 5 },
        { type: "return", target: "NPC_Guard" }
      ]
      rewards: { gold: 100, xp: 50 }
    }
  }

  logic {
    // Quest giver → Quest activation flow
    on_interact("NPC_Guard") {
      if (Quest_SlayGoblins.status == "available") {
        ui.show_quest_offer(Quest_SlayGoblins)
      } else if (Quest_SlayGoblins.status == "active" && 
                 Quest_SlayGoblins.current_objective == 2) {
        Quest_SlayGoblins.complete()
        Player.gold += Quest_SlayGoblins.rewards.gold
      }
    }

    // Accept button → Quest.accept() flow
    on_accept_quest(quest) {
      quest.accept()
    }

    // Kill event → Objective progress flow
    on_enemy_death(enemy) {
      for (quest in active_quests()) {
        let obj = quest.current_objective_data()
        if (obj.type == "kill" && enemy.type == obj.target) {
          obj.increment()
        }
      }
    }

    // Objective complete → Quest advance flow
    on_event("objective_complete", obj) {
      obj.parent_quest.advance()
      ui.toast("Objective Complete!")
    }

    // Quest complete → Reward flow
    on_event("quest_complete", quest) {
      Player.gold += quest.rewards.gold
      Player.xp += quest.rewards.xp
      ui.show_rewards(quest.rewards)
    }
  }
}
```

**The flow visualization:**
```
[Talk to Guard] → [Accept] → [Kill 5 Goblins] → [Return] → [Rewards]
       ↓              ↓            ↓                ↓           ↓
    (checks       (status      (tracks          (turns      (gold/xp
     quest         changes)     kills)           in)         given)
     status)
```

Each quest is a node, each objective is a sub-node, and completion flows forward through the chain.

Player death is a **convergent flow** - many things can cause it, but they all lead to the same outcome.

**The death flow graph:**
```
[Enemy Attack] ──────┐
                     │
[Fall Damage] ───────┼──→ [Health ≤ 0] ──→ [Death] ──→ [Respawn]
                     │          │              │           │
[Poison/DoT] ────────┤          │              │           │
                     │          ↓              ↓           ↓
[Trap Triggered] ────┘      [Effects]      [Penalty]   [Reset]
                           - screen red    - lose gold  - heal
                           - slow-mo       - drop items - teleport
                           - sound         - xp loss    - invuln
```

**Pattern 1: Health Watcher (Reactive)**
```holo
logic {
  // Single convergence point - all damage flows here
  on_health_change("Player") {
    if (Player.health <= 0) {
      trigger_death()
    }
  }
}
```

**Pattern 2: Explicit Death Event (Cleaner)**
```holo
template "Mortal" {
  state { health: 100, max_health: 100 }

  action take_damage(amount, source) {
    this.health -= amount
    emit("damaged", { target: this, amount, source })

    if (this.health <= 0) {
      this.health = 0
      emit("death", { target: this, killer: source })
    }
  }
}

logic {
  // Clean separation - damage and death are different events
  on_event("death", data) {
    if (data.target == Player) {
      handle_player_death(data.killer)
    }
  }
}
```

**Pattern 3: Death State Machine**
```holo
template "Player" {
  state {
    health: 100
    alive: true
    respawn_point: [0, 0, 0]
    death_penalty: 0.1  // Lose 10% gold
  }

  action die() {
    if (!this.alive) return  // Prevent double-death

    this.alive = false
    this.disable_input()

    // Death sequence
    emit("player_died")
  }

  action respawn() {
    this.alive = true
    this.health = this.max_health
    this.position = this.respawn_point
    this.enable_input()
    this.grant_invulnerability(3000)

    emit("player_respawned")
  }
}

logic {
  // Death effects flow
  on_event("player_died") {
    // Visual
    camera.fade_to_black(1000)
    audio.play("death_sound")

    // Penalty
    let gold_lost = floor(Player.gold * Player.death_penalty)
    Player.gold -= gold_lost
    spawn("GoldDrop", Player.position, { amount: gold_lost })

    // Respawn timer
    after(3000) {
      Player.respawn()
    }
  }

  on_event("player_respawned") {
    camera.fade_from_black(500)
    ui.toast("You have respawned")
  }
}
```

**Key insight:** Death is where multiple damage flows **converge**, then **branch** into effects, penalty, and respawn. Design it as a funnel:

```
    Many inputs
         │
         ↓
    [Health ≤ 0]
         │
         ↓
     ┌───┴───┐
     ↓       ↓
 [Effects] [Penalty]
     │       │
     └───┬───┘
         ↓
    [Respawn]
```

A day/night cycle is a **global state machine** that affects many nodes simultaneously.

**The cycle as a circular graph:**
```
    ┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
    │                                      │
    ↓                                      │
[Dawn] ──→ [Day] ──→ [Dusk] ──→ [Night] ──┘
  │          │         │          │
  ↓          ↓         ↓          ↓
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│        Affects all these:           │
│  - Sky color                        │
│  - Lighting intensity               │
│  - NPC schedules                    │
│  - Enemy spawns                     │
│  - Shop hours                       │
│  - Ambient sounds                   │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**The broadcast pattern:**

Time changes → broadcasts to all listeners → each node reacts appropriately

```holo
composition "Day Night Cycle" {

  // Global time state
  environment {
    time_of_day: 0.0      // 0.0 = midnight, 0.5 = noon, 1.0 = midnight
    day_length_ms: 600000  // 10 minutes = 1 day
    current_phase: "night"
  }

  // Phase definitions
  const PHASES = {
    dawn:  { start: 0.2, end: 0.3, sky: "#FFB347", light: 0.4 },
    day:   { start: 0.3, end: 0.7, sky: "#87CEEB", light: 1.0 },
    dusk:  { start: 0.7, end: 0.8, sky: "#FF6B6B", light: 0.4 },
    night: { start: 0.8, end: 0.2, sky: "#1a1a2e", light: 0.1 }
  }

  spatial_group "World" {
    // Sun/moon that rotates
    orb Sun {
      position: [0, 100, 0]
      traits: ["light-source"]
      intensity: 1.0
    }

    orb Moon {
      position: [0, -100, 0]
      traits: ["light-source"]
      intensity: 0.2
      visible: false
    }

    // NPCs that react to time
    object "Shopkeeper" using "NPC" {
      position: [10, 0, 5]
      schedule: {
        work_start: 0.3,   // Opens at dawn
        work_end: 0.7      // Closes at dusk
      }
    }

    object "NightGuard" using "NPC" {
      position: [15, 0, 0]
      schedule: {
        work_start: 0.75,  // Starts at dusk
        work_end: 0.25     // Ends at dawn
      }
    }

    // Enemies that spawn at night
    orb WolfSpawner {
      position: [50, 0, 50]
      active_phases: ["night"]
      spawn_rate: 5000
    }
  }

  logic {
    // Core time advancement (the clock ticks)
    every(100) {
      // Advance time
      time_of_day += (100 / day_length_ms)
      if (time_of_day >= 1.0) time_of_day = 0.0

      // Check for phase transitions
      let new_phase = calculate_phase(time_of_day)
      if (new_phase != current_phase) {
        let old_phase = current_phase
        current_phase = new_phase
        broadcast("phase_changed", { from: old_phase, to: new_phase })
      }
    }

    // Smooth sky/lighting updates
    every(1000) {
      let phase_data = PHASES[current_phase]
      sky.lerp_color(phase_data.sky, 0.1)
      Sun.intensity = lerp(Sun.intensity, phase_data.light, 0.1)

      // Rotate sun based on time
      let angle = time_of_day * 360
      Sun.position = rotate_around_origin([0, 100, 0], angle)
      Moon.position = rotate_around_origin([0, 100, 0], angle + 180)
    }

    // === LISTENERS - Nodes react to phase changes ===

    // Shops open/close
    on_broadcast("phase_changed", data) {
      for (npc in NPCs) {
        if (npc.schedule) {
          let should_work = is_in_schedule(time_of_day, npc.schedule)
          if (should_work && !npc.working) {
            npc.start_work()
          } else if (!should_work && npc.working) {
            npc.end_work()
          }
        }
      }
    }

    // Night enemy spawning
    on_broadcast("phase_changed", data) {
      if (data.to == "night") {
        WolfSpawner.enabled = true
        ui.toast("Dangerous creatures emerge...")
      } else if (data.from == "night") {
        WolfSpawner.enabled = false
        despawn_all("Wolf")  // Wolves flee at dawn
      }
    }

    // Ambient audio changes
    on_broadcast("phase_changed", data) {
      match data.to {
        "dawn" => audio.crossfade("birds_morning", 2000)
        "day" => audio.crossfade("ambient_day", 2000)
        "dusk" => audio.crossfade("crickets_evening", 2000)
        "night" => audio.crossfade("owls_night", 2000)
      }
    }

    // Lights turn on/off
    on_broadcast("phase_changed", data) {
      if (data.to == "night" || data.to == "dusk") {
        for (torch in Torches) {
          torch.light_up()
        }
      } else {
        for (torch in Torches) {
          torch.extinguish()
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**The key pattern is hub-and-spoke:**

```
                    [Time System]
                         │
              broadcasts phase_changed
                         │
         ┌───────────────┼───────────────┐
         ↓               ↓               ↓
    [NPCs]          [Spawners]       [Lighting]
   schedules        active/off       intensity
         │               │               │
         ↓               ↓               ↓
   [Shopkeeper]    [WolfSpawner]    [Torches]
   open/close      spawn wolves    light up
```

One global clock, many listeners - clean separation of concerns.

You've identified the core problem - your graph has **nodes but no edges**.

**Disconnected scene (what you have):**
```
[Player]    [Chest]    [Enemy]    [Door]    [Key]
    ○          ○          ○         ○         ○

    (just floating objects, no relationships)
```

**Connected scene (what you need):**
```
[Player] ──kills──→ [Enemy] ──drops──→ [Key]
    │                                    │
    │                                    ↓
    ├──opens──→ [Chest] ──contains──→ [Loot]
    │
    └──unlocks─────────────────────→ [Door] (requires Key)
                                        │
                                        ↓
                                   [Next Area]
```

**How to connect your scene:**

**Step 1: Identify natural relationships**

Ask yourself:
- What can the Player **do** to each object?
- What does each object **produce** or **enable**?
- What **requires** something else first?

**Step 2: Draw the edges**

```holo
logic {
  // === PLAYER → OBJECT connections ===

  // Player can kill Enemy
  on_attack("Enemy") {
    Enemy.health -= Player.damage
    if (Enemy.health <= 0) {
      emit("enemy_died", Enemy)
    }
  }

  // Player can open Chest
  on_interact("Chest") {
    if (!Chest.opened) {
      Chest.opened = true
      spawn_loot(Chest.contents, Chest.position)
    }
  }

  // Player can use Door (conditional)
  on_interact("Door") {
    if (Player.has_item("Key")) {
      Door.unlock()
      Door.open()
    } else {
      ui.toast("This door is locked. You need a key.")
    }
  }

  // === OBJECT → OBJECT connections ===

  // Enemy drops Key on death
  on_event("enemy_died", enemy) {
    spawn("Key", enemy.position)
    despawn(enemy)
  }

  // Key can be picked up
  on_collect("Key") {
    Player.add_to_inventory(Key)
    ui.toast("Got the Key!")
  }

  // === OBJECT → WORLD connections ===

  // Door leads somewhere
  on_door_opened("Door") {
    // Enable passage to next area
    NextAreaTrigger.enabled = true
  }
}
```

**Step 3: Add feedback so players see the connections**

```holo
logic {
  // Visual hints show potential connections
  on_player_near("Chest", 3) {
    if (!Chest.opened) {
      Chest.show_interact_prompt("Open")
    }
  }

  on_player_near("Door", 3) {
    if (Player.has_item("Key")) {
      Door.show_interact_prompt("Unlock")
    } else {
      Door.show_interact_prompt("Locked", "red")
    }
  }
}
```

**The formula for connection:**

```
EVERY OBJECT should have:
1. At least one INCOMING edge (how player/world affects it)
2. At least one OUTGOING edge (what it produces/enables)
3. A FEEDBACK mechanism (how player knows about the connection)
```

**Checklist for your objects:**

| Object | Incoming Edge | Outgoing Edge | Feedback |
|--------|--------------|---------------|----------|
| Enemy  | attack → damage | death → drops loot | Health bar, death anim |
| Chest  | interact → open | open → spawn items | Glow, prompt, sound |
| Key    | collect → inventory | unlock → opens door | Sparkle, pickup sound |
| Door   | use key → unlock | open → access area | Lock icon, door swing |

When every object has edges in and out, your game feels like a **connected world** instead of a **prop museum**.

Object awareness is about **creating edges** between nodes. There are several patterns:

**Pattern 1: Direct Reference (Static Edges)**

Objects know about each other by name:

```holo
object "Guard" {
  watches: "Prisoner"  // Direct reference
  alert_target: "Alarm"
}

logic {
  every(1000) {
    if (Prisoner.escaped) {
      Alarm.trigger()  // Guard knows about Alarm
    }
  }
}
```

```
[Guard] ──watches──→ [Prisoner]
    │
    └──alerts──→ [Alarm]
```

**Pattern 2: Proximity Detection (Dynamic Edges)**

Objects discover each other at runtime:

```holo
logic {
  every(500) {
    for (enemy in Enemies) {
      // Find all objects within range
      let nearby = find_in_radius(enemy.position, enemy.sight_range)

      for (obj in nearby) {
        if (obj.type == "Player") {
          enemy.target = obj  // Dynamic edge created
          enemy.enter_chase_mode()
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

```
[Enemy] ──?──→ (scans area)
                   │
         finds [Player]
                   │
                   ↓
[Enemy] ──targets──→ [Player]  (edge created)
```

**Pattern 3: Event Subscription (Loose Coupling)**

Objects listen for events without knowing who sends them:

```holo
// The sender doesn't know who's listening
object "Alarm" {
  action trigger() {
    broadcast("alarm_triggered", { location: this.position })
  }
}

// Multiple objects react independently
logic {
  on_broadcast("alarm_triggered", data) {
    // All guards hear it
    for (guard in Guards) {
      guard.investigate(data.location)
    }

    // Lights turn on
    for (light in SecurityLights) {
      light.turn_on()
    }

    // Doors lock
    for (door in SecurityDoors) {
      door.lock()
    }
  }
}
```

```
                [Alarm]
                   │
            broadcasts event
                   │
       ┌───────────┼───────────┐
       ↓           ↓           ↓
   [Guards]    [Lights]    [Doors]
  investigate   turn on      lock
```

**Pattern 4: Tag-Based Grouping**

Objects find each other by traits:

```holo
// Mark objects with traits
orb Crystal_1 { traits: ["destructible", "crystal"] }
orb Crystal_2 { traits: ["destructible", "crystal"] }
orb Pillar { traits: ["destructible", "stone"] }

logic {
  // Find all objects with a trait
  on_spell_cast("shatter") {
    let targets = find_by_trait("crystal")  // Finds Crystal_1 and Crystal_2
    for (t in targets) {
      t.shatter()
    }
  }
}
```

```
[Spell] ──finds trait "crystal"──→ [Crystal_1]
                                    [Crystal_2]
              (Pillar not affected - wrong trait)
```

**Pattern 5: Parent-Child Hierarchy**

Objects know their container:

```holo
spatial_group "Inventory" {
  orb Slot_1 { item: null, parent: "Inventory" }
  orb Slot_2 { item: null, parent: "Inventory" }
  orb Slot_3 { item: null, parent: "Inventory" }
}

logic {
  on_collect(item) {
    // Find empty slot in parent container
    let slot = Inventory.find_empty_slot()
    if (slot) {
      slot.item = item
    }
  }

  on_drop(slot) {
    let item = slot.item
    slot.item = null
    spawn(item, Player.position)
  }
}
```

```
    [Inventory]
         │
    ┌────┼────┐
    ↓    ↓    ↓
[Slot1][Slot2][Slot3]
   │
   └── contains [Sword]
```

**Choosing the right pattern:**

| Pattern | Use When | Example |
|---------|----------|----------|
| Direct Reference | Fixed relationships | Guard always watches same door |
| Proximity | Dynamic discovery | Enemy finds player in range |
| Events | Many-to-many | Alarm alerts all guards |
| Tags | Group behavior | Spell affects all crystals |
| Hierarchy | Container/contents | Inventory slots |

**The key insight:** Awareness = edges in your graph. More edges = more interconnected gameplay.
